TY  - JOUR
AU  - Khomyn, Marta
AU  - Putniņs̆, Tālis
AU  - Zoican, Marius
T1  - The Value of ETF Liquidity
PY  - 2024
Y1  - 2024/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhae041
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 37
IS  - 10
SP  - 3092
EP  - 3148
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We analyze how ETFs compete. Drawing on a new model and empirical analysis, we show that ETF secondary market liquidity plays a key role in determining fees. More liquid ETFs for a given index charge higher fees and attract short-horizon investors who are more sensitive to liquidity than to fees. Higher turnover from these investors sustains the ETF’s high liquidity, allowing the ETF to extract a rent through its fee, and creating a first-mover advantage. Liquidity segmentation through clientele effects generates welfare losses. Our findings resolve the apparent paradox that higher-fee ETFs not only survive but also flourish in equilibrium.
Y2  - 10/27/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhae041
ER  - 



